1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,139
Have you ever over thought something so much that you ended up doing absolutely nothing?

2
00:00:05,980 --> 00:00:06,519
Oh yeah.

3
00:00:07,900 --> 00:00:09,720
My brain loves that strategy.

4
00:00:11,099 --> 00:00:12,660
Step 1. Panic

5
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:16,260
Step 2. Panic about the panic.

6
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:23,660
Exactly. It's like our brain thinks thinking more will somehow magically fix everything.

7
00:00:24,420 --> 00:00:26,960
My brain is like a broken search engine.

8
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:32,500
I ask one question and it opens 47 tabs of anxiety.

9
00:00:33,480 --> 00:00:35,280
And none of them are helpful.

10
00:00:36,179 --> 00:00:37,560
Not a single one.

11
00:00:38,740 --> 00:00:40,640
Just emotional pop-up ads.

12
00:00:42,060 --> 00:00:48,479
Today we're talking about how to stop overthinking, face fears, and take action in life.

13
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:53,039
Yeah, because I'm an expert at doing nothing due to overthinking.

14
00:00:53,980 --> 00:00:56,179
Well, we'll get into that.

15
00:00:56,759 --> 00:00:59,439
But first, let's introduce the topic.

16
00:01:00,219 --> 00:01:01,679
So overthinking.

17
00:01:03,159 --> 00:01:05,640
It's like the ultimate productivity killer.

18
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:07,319
Right?

19
00:01:07,939 --> 00:01:13,579
It's like our brain is trying to protect us, but it ends up paralyzing us.

20
00:01:14,180 --> 00:01:17,879
Last, yeah, my brain is like a helicopter parent.

21
00:01:19,079 --> 00:01:20,459
Chuckles, okay?

22
00:01:20,459 --> 00:01:23,760
So, let's dive into a personal story.

23
00:01:24,379 --> 00:01:26,140
Oh boy, this should be good.

24
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:30,599
So, I used to be terrified of public speaking.

25
00:01:31,359 --> 00:01:34,159
I would overthink every possible scenario.

26
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:35,819
Interrupting.

27
00:01:36,040 --> 00:01:37,340
Oh, I can relate.

28
00:01:38,760 --> 00:01:43,459
I once had to give a presentation and I was so nervous I forgot my own name.

29
00:01:44,760 --> 00:01:45,159
Laughs.

30
00:01:45,760 --> 00:01:46,640
That's amazing.

31
00:01:46,640 --> 00:01:51,680
But for me, it was more like, what if I say something stupid?

32
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:53,120
Joakingly.

33
00:01:53,560 --> 00:01:55,799
Oh, that's never happened to me.

34
00:01:57,159 --> 00:01:57,879
Laughs, right.

35
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:03,159
But seriously, I had to face my fear and just start speaking.

36
00:02:04,060 --> 00:02:05,200
And how did that go?

37
00:02:06,620 --> 00:02:08,759
It was actually really liberating.

38
00:02:09,460 --> 00:02:13,400
I realized that people aren't as judgmental as I thought.

39
00:02:14,120 --> 00:02:17,460
Teasingly, yeah, until you say something stupid.

40
00:02:18,919 --> 00:02:21,460
Laughs, hey, that's not the point.

41
00:02:22,259 --> 00:02:24,039
Smirking, okay, okay.

42
00:02:25,560 --> 00:02:28,819
So what's a common situation where people overthink?

43
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:35,560
Well, like when you're trying to make a big decision, like what career to choose.

44
00:02:36,319 --> 00:02:38,699
Oh yeah, or what to eat for breakfast?

45
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:41,659
Laughs exactly.

46
00:02:42,539 --> 00:02:46,780
Our brain can turn anything into a monumental decision.

47
00:02:47,099 --> 00:02:50,780
Joakingly, I mean, what if I choose the wrong cereal?

48
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:53,180
Chuckles, right.

49
00:02:53,960 --> 00:02:59,259
But seriously, it's like our brain is trying to weigh every possible outcome.

50
00:02:59,939 --> 00:03:02,319
And that's when the anxiety kicks in.

51
00:03:03,639 --> 00:03:04,300
Exactly.

52
00:03:05,039 --> 00:03:07,900
So let's talk about why humans overthink.

53
00:03:08,620 --> 00:03:13,620
Curiously, yeah, is it just me or is it a human thing?

54
00:03:14,379 --> 00:03:17,080
Thoughtfully, I think it's a mix of both.

55
00:03:17,599 --> 00:03:21,580
Our brain is wired to anticipate potential dangers.

56
00:03:22,319 --> 00:03:25,580
Joakingly, like what if a dinosaur attacks?

57
00:03:26,860 --> 00:03:32,840
Laughs, well, maybe not dinosaurs, but more like what if I fail?

58
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:38,419
Smirking, yeah, or what if I succeed and have to deal with the consequences?

59
00:03:40,020 --> 00:03:41,300
Laughs exactly.

60
00:03:42,020 --> 00:03:48,039
But seriously, our brain is trying to protect us, but it can get carried away.

61
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:51,639
Curiously, so how do we stop it?

62
00:03:52,680 --> 00:03:58,379
Well, one strategy is to set a timer and limit your thinking time.

63
00:03:59,019 --> 00:04:03,419
Joakingly, oh, like a thinking timeout.

64
00:04:03,639 --> 00:04:04,900
Laughs exactly.

65
00:04:05,639 --> 00:04:09,979
And another strategy is to focus on the present moment.

66
00:04:10,659 --> 00:04:13,039
Thoughtfully, yeah, like mindfulness.

67
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:15,340
Exactly.

68
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,259
And finally, just take action.

69
00:04:18,980 --> 00:04:20,199
Don't wait for perfection.

70
00:04:21,180 --> 00:04:23,540
Excitedly, yeah, just do it.

71
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:25,540
Like Nike.

72
00:04:27,359 --> 00:04:28,560
Smiling exactly.

73
00:04:29,259 --> 00:04:31,500
And that's what we want to leave you with today.

74
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:36,259
Inspiringly, yeah, don't let overthinking hold you back.

75
00:04:37,420 --> 00:04:38,600
Just take the leap.

76
00:04:39,959 --> 00:04:42,500
Smiling, thanks for tuning in everyone.

77
00:04:43,439 --> 00:04:48,720
Joakingly, and if you're still overthinking, just remember, it's not the end of the world.

78
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:53,199
Laughs, unless you're actually facing a dinosaur.

79
00:04:53,199 --> 00:04:56,040
Laughs, then you're on your own.
